   464→<section class="lesson" id="s1">
   465→  <div class="lesson-head"><div class="lesson-num">01</div><h2>What is a Coding Assistant?</h2></div>
   466→  <p>A <strong>coding assistant</strong> is a tool that sits between you and a language model (like Claude), helping you write, fix, and manage code. It can read your files, run your tests, and make changes — all from a single conversation.</p>
   467→
   468→  <h3>The Core Workflow</h3>
   469→  <div class="steps">
   470→    <div class="step"><div class="step-rail"><div class="step-dot"></div><div class="step-line"></div></div><div class="step-body"><div class="step-title">You send a task</div><div class="step-text">"Fix the login bug described in this error message"</div></div></div>
   471→    <div class="step"><div class="step-rail"><div class="step-dot"></div><div class="step-line"></div></div><div class="step-body"><div class="step-title">Assistant wraps the request</div><div class="step-text">The coding assistant layer adds tool instructions to your message</div></div></div>
   472→    <div class="step"><div class="step-rail"><div class="step-dot"></div><div class="step-line"></div></div><div class="step-body"><div class="step-title">Model gathers context</div><div class="step-text">Reads relevant files, understands the codebase structure</div></div></div>
   473→    <div class="step"><div class="step-rail"><div class="step-dot"></div><div class="step-line"></div></div><div class="step-body"><div class="step-title">Plan is formulated</div><div class="step-text">A step-by-step approach is created before any changes</div></div></div>
   474→    <div class="step"><div class="step-rail"><div class="step-dot"></div></div><div class="step-body"><div class="step-title">Action is taken</div><div class="step-text">Files are edited, tests run, and results returned to you</div></div></div>
   475→  </div>
   476→
   477→  <div class="analogy"><p>Imagine hiring a freelance developer. You email them: "our checkout page is broken." A good developer doesn't guess — they look at the code, reproduce the issue, trace the logic, then fix it. A coding assistant works the same way, but faster.</p></div>
   478→
   479→  <div class="callout info">
   480→    <span class="callout-label">Key Limitation</span>
   481→    <p>Language models can only process text input and produce text output. They cannot directly read files, run commands, or interact with external systems. This is why <strong>tool use</strong> is essential.</p>
   482→  </div>
   483→</section>
   484→
   485→<!-- ══════════════ LESSON 2 ══════════════ -->
   486→<section class="lesson" id="s2">
   487→  <div class="lesson-head"><div class="lesson-num">02</div><h2>What is Claude Code?</h2></div>
   488→  <p><strong>Claude Code</strong> is Anthropic's official coding assistant built on the Claude language model. You interact with it through the terminal, and it can read files, write code, run commands, and connect to external services.</p>
   489→
   490→  <h3>Why Claude Code?</h3>
   491→  <div class="table-wrap"><table>
   492→    <thead><tr><th>Feature</th><th>What It Means for You</th></tr></thead>
   493→    <tbody>
   494→      <tr><td><strong>Superior tool use</strong></td><td>Exceptionally good at knowing which tool to use and when — better than competing models</td></tr>
   495→      <tr><td><strong>Extensible by design</strong></td><td>Plug in new tools (browsers, databases, APIs) as your needs grow via MCP servers</td></tr>
   496→      <tr><td><strong>Better security</strong></td><td>Searches your code directly — doesn't send your entire codebase to external indexing servers</td></tr>
   497→      <tr><td><strong>Complex task handling</strong></td><td>Chains multiple tools together to solve multi-step problems effectively</td></tr>
   498→    </tbody>
   499→  </table></div>
   500→</section>
   501→
   502→<!-- ══════════════ LESSON 3 ══════════════ -->
   503→<section class="lesson" id="s3">
   504→  <div class="lesson-head"><div class="lesson-num">03</div><h2>How Tool Use Works</h2></div>
   505→  <p>This is the most important concept to internalize. <strong>Language models can only process text.</strong> They cannot open a file, run a command, or check a website on their own. Tool use is the mechanism that bridges this gap.</p>
   506→
   507→  <h3>Step-by-Step Breakdown</h3>
   508→  <pre data-lang="conversation"><code><span class="cc">// 1. You ask:</span>
   509→<span class="cs">"What's in my package.json?"</span>
   510→
   511→<span class="cc">// 2. Claude Code adds instructions to the request:</span>
   512→<span class="cs">"If you need to read a file, respond with: READ_FILE: &lt;filename&gt;"</span>
   513→
   514→<span class="cc">// 3. The language model responds:</span>
   515→<span class="cn">READ_FILE</span>: package.json
   516→
   517→<span class="cc">// 4. Claude Code (assistant layer) actually reads the file</span>
   518→
   519→<span class="cc">// 5. File contents are sent back to the language model</span>
   520→
   521→<span class="cc">// 6. Claude reads the content and gives you a real answer</span></code></pre>
   522→
   523→  <div class="analogy"><p>Think of a surgeon and a scrub nurse. The surgeon (language model) says "scalpel" and the nurse (Claude Code) physically hands it over. The surgeon has the knowledge; the nurse does the physical work. Together they complete the operation.</p></div>
   524→
   525→  <div class="callout gold">
   526→    <span class="callout-label">Remember</span>
   527→    <p>All language models require tool use for non-text tasks. The quality of tool use directly impacts how effective a coding assistant is. Claude's strength here is what makes Claude Code powerful.</p>
   528→  </div>
   529→</section>
   530→
   531→<!-- ══════════════ LESSON 4 ══════════════ -->
   532→<section class="lesson" id="s4">
   533→  <div class="lesson-head"><div class="lesson-num">04</div><h2>Claude Code in Action</h2></div>
   534→
   535→  <h3>Example 1 — Performance Optimization</h3>
   536→  <p>Claude analyzed the <strong>Chalk JavaScript library</strong> (~430M weekly downloads) and achieved a <strong>3.9× throughput improvement</strong>:</p>
   537→  <div class="steps">
   538→    <div class="step"><div class="step-rail"><div class="step-dot"></div><div class="step-line"></div></div><div class="step-body"><div class="step-title">Benchmark</div><div class="step-text">Runs baseline performance benchmarks to measure current speed</div></div></div>
   539→    <div class="step"><div class="step-rail"><div class="step-dot"></div><div class="step-line"></div></div><div class="step-body"><div class="step-title">Profile</div><div class="step-text">Uses profiling tools to find the slowest code paths</div></div></div>
   540→    <div class="step"><div class="step-rail"><div class="step-dot"></div><div class="step-line"></div></div><div class="step-body"><div class="step-title">Plan</div><div class="step-text">Creates a prioritized to-do list of bottlenecks to fix</div></div></div>
   541→    <div class="step"><div class="step-rail"><div class="step-dot"></div></div><div class="step-body"><div class="step-title">Fix & Verify</div><div class="step-text">Implements changes and re-runs benchmarks to confirm improvement</div></div></div>
